<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1924-09-11T02:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1924-09-11T02:00:00-05:00" n="326" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d326">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/5509: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Bell</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1924-09-11T15:00:00+08:00"><hi rend="italic">September 11,
                                        1924—3 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received September 11—9:14
                                a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>339. My 334, September 8, 5 p.m. Senior consul Shanghai reports defense
                            commissioner on the one side and Nanking admiral on the other have both
                            agreed to the neutralization of the Whangpoo River and to the revocation
                            of the regulations regarding navigation of the lower Yangtze and of the
                            Whangpoo.</p>
                        <p>This if true is very satisfactory.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Bell</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>